## 4. Frame & Event System

### 4.1 Creating Frames

```lua
local frame = CreateFrame("Frame", "MyAddonFrame", UIParent)
frame:SetSize(200, 100)
frame:SetPoint("CENTER")
```

- First arg: frame type (`"Frame"`, `"Button"`, `"EditBox"`, `"ScrollFrame"`, `"StatusBar"`, `"GameTooltip"`, `"CheckButton"`, `"Slider"`, etc.)
- Second arg: global name (or nil for anonymous frames). **Minimize global names** — only name frames that must be accessed by XML or secure templates.
- Third arg: parent frame.
- Optional fourth arg: template string(s), comma-separated.

### 4.2 Event Handling — Frame-Based (Traditional)

```lua
local f = CreateFrame("Frame")
f:RegisterEvent("PLAYER_ENTERING_WORLD")
f:RegisterEvent("PLAYER_LOGIN")
f:SetScript("OnEvent", function(self, event, ...)
    if event == "PLAYER_ENTERING_WORLD" then
        local isLogin, isReload = ...
        -- handle
    elseif event == "PLAYER_LOGIN" then
        -- handle
    end
end)
```

### 4.3 Event Handling — EventRegistry (Modern)

```lua
-- For Blizzard frame events:
EventRegistry:RegisterFrameEventAndCallback("PLAYER_ENTERING_WORLD",
    function(ownerID, isLogin, isReload)
        -- handle
    end
)

-- For custom / FrameXML callback events:
EventRegistry:RegisterCallback("CollectionsJournal.TabSet",
    function(ownerID, journal, tabID)
        -- handle
    end
)
```

EventRegistry is built into FrameXML and does NOT require creating a frame.
The first parameter to callback is always `ownerID` (used for unregistering), followed by event payload.

### 4.4 Important Events

- `ADDON_LOADED` — fires per-addon; check `arg1 == addonName`. Good place to initialize SavedVariables.
- `PLAYER_LOGIN` — fires once, after all addons are loaded and the player exists in the world. Safe to query unit info.
- `PLAYER_ENTERING_WORLD` — fires on login, reload, and every zone transition (loading screens). Args: `isLogin`, `isReload`.
- `PLAYER_LOGOUT` — last chance to write to SavedVariables.

### 4.5 Slash Commands

```lua
SLASH_MYADDON1 = "/myaddon"
SLASH_MYADDON2 = "/ma"
SlashCmdList["MYADDON"] = function(msg)
    local cmd, rest = strsplit(" ", msg, 2)
    -- handle commands
end
```

### 4.6 Backdrop & Positioning

**SetBackdrop resets colors:** With `BackdropTemplate`, **`Frame:SetBackdrop(backdrop)` resets backdrop colors to defaults** (typically white). You must re-apply colors after any `SetBackdrop` call.

```lua
-- BAD: background will appear white after SetBackdrop
frame:SetBackdrop(BACKDROP_INNER_NO_INSETS)

-- GOOD: always pair SetBackdrop with color calls
frame:SetBackdrop(BACKDROP_INNER_NO_INSETS)
frame:SetBackdropColor(OneWoW_GUI:GetThemeColor("BG_PRIMARY"))
frame:SetBackdropBorderColor(OneWoW_GUI:GetThemeColor("BORDER_DEFAULT"))
```

This applies even when replacing a backdrop set by a factory (e.g. `OneWoW_GUI:CreateFrame`). Calling `SetBackdrop(nil)` and re-setting does not help — you must call `SetBackdropColor` and `SetBackdropBorderColor` after `SetBackdrop`.

**Overriding SetPoint:** To override a frame's existing anchor, call **`ClearAllPoints()`** before `SetPoint()`. Otherwise the new `SetPoint` may be ignored or conflict with prior anchors.

```lua
-- BAD: may not override existing anchor
divider:SetPoint("TOPLEFT", parent, "TOPLEFT", 1, -29)

-- GOOD: clear first when changing anchors
divider:ClearAllPoints()
divider:SetPoint("TOPLEFT", parent, "TOPLEFT", 1, -29)
```

### 4.7 Popup / Dropdown Dismiss — OnUpdate Hybrid Pattern

WoW has no click-through or event-bubbling for sibling frames.
A fullscreen overlay **above** the host catches all clicks but **consumes** them (two-click to activate a control). An overlay **below** the host lets controls receive clicks but never fires for in-host dismiss.

**Solution — OnUpdate watcher:** WoW processes input (OnClick, OnMouseDown) **before** running OnUpdate scripts in the same frame.
Use an `OnUpdate` on the popup that detects `IsMouseButtonDown` transitions while `IsMouseOver()` is false: the clicked control fires first, then OnUpdate hides the popup.

```lua
-- On the popup/menu frame, after creation:
local wasDown = IsMouseButtonDown("LeftButton") or IsMouseButtonDown("RightButton")
menu:SetScript("OnUpdate", function(self)
    local isDown = IsMouseButtonDown("LeftButton") or IsMouseButtonDown("RightButton")
    if isDown and not wasDown then
        if not self:IsMouseOver() then
            self:Hide()
        end
    end
    wasDown = isDown
end)
```

Pair with a **game-world overlay** (fullscreen `UIParent` Button) at `hostLevel - 2` (below the host, same strata) to block 3D viewport interaction while the popup is open.
The overlay only catches clicks in areas not covered by the host window.

**Key rules:**
- Initialize `wasDown` from current button state so a popup opened mid-click doesn't immediately self-close.
- `IsMouseOver()` checks the frame's bounding rect; all children within those bounds (search box, scroll frame, items) are covered.
- Do **not** use a fullscreen overlay above the host for dismiss — it consumes the click and forces a second click to activate controls.
- Do **not** sprinkle explicit close calls at every navigation boundary (tab switches, list selections). The OnUpdate handles this automatically.

### 4.8 FontString Local Overrides & SetFontObject

`SetFontObject(fontObj)` on a FontString sets the inheritance source but does **NOT** clear local property overrides created by explicit setter calls.
Once you call `SetJustifyH("RIGHT")` (or `SetTextColor`, `SetFont`, etc.) directly on a FontString, that local override **persists across all subsequent `SetFontObject()` calls** — the font object's inherited value is shadowed.

```lua
-- BAD: local override from SetJustifyH persists across SetFontObject changes
fs:SetFontObject(RightAlignedFont)   -- justify = RIGHT (from font object)
fs:SetJustifyH("RIGHT")             -- creates local override "RIGHT"
fs:SetFontObject(CenterAlignedFont)  -- font object says CENTER, but...
print(fs:GetJustifyH())              -- "RIGHT" — stale local override!
```

**Key rules:**
- `GetJustifyH()` on FontString returns the **local override** if one exists, otherwise the font object's inherited value. You cannot distinguish which source provided the value.
- `GetJustifyH()` on a **Font object** always returns correct effective value (including values inherited from parent fonts in the XML chain).
- **Reusing a FontString** to display different font objects over time will accumulate stale local overrides from previous selections. This causes properties from previous font to "stick" to next one.
- **Preferred pattern:** When FontString must cycle through different font objects (e.g. a font preview/browser), **recreate the FontString** each time rather than reusing it. This guarantees a clean slate with no local overrides.
Examples:

  ```lua
  -- Recreate to ensure no stale overrides from previous font
  if tab.previewFS then tab.previewFS:Hide() end
  tab.previewFS = parent:CreateFontString(nil, "ARTWORK")
  tab.previewFS:SetFontObject(newFontObj)  -- sole authority for all properties
  ```

- If recreating is not feasible, read property values from the **Font object** (not the FontString) and re-apply them explicitly every time:

  ```lua
  fs:SetFontObject(fontObj)
  -- Read from Font object — always returns correct inherited value
  fs:SetJustifyH(fontObj:GetJustifyH())
  -- Do NOT read from fs:GetJustifyH() — may return stale local override
  ```

